      <bioghist id="aspace_f0b53a26a85a7109b3d6247dc9ffadba">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>The Department of Design was established at Yale University in 1950, with Josef Albers as chairman. Alvin Eisenman was hired as the first Lecturer in Graphic Arts and became the first director in graphic arts (later called graphic design) in 1951. Initially an undergraduate program, graphic design soon became a graduate program focused on professional practice rather than fine arts. The early curriculum focused on typography, photography, printmaking, and the production and design of printed materials. Although the term had been in use for decades, Yale was the first university to establish a degree program in graphic design. Eisenman led the department until 1990, and continued to teach in the program through the 1990s. Sheila Levrant de Bretteville was appointed professor and director of graduate studies in graphic design in 1990. She was succeeded in 2022 by Nontsikelelo Mutiti.</p>
         <p>Alvin Lustig, a Visiting Lecturer in the department from 1951-1953, taught that "The solution to any design problem lies within an analysis of the problem." "Problem books" were a collection of exercises and situations designed to teach students to solve these problems with design.</p>
      </bioghist>
